=Below are emails to the client for gifts the client has bought for important people in their life. Each email may contain more than one gift, or just one.

The client's name is related to the strings below, and the client is NEVER a valid recipient. None of the emails are gifts the client bought for themself. 

<Client Name Strings>
{{ $input.all().map(x => x.json.extracted_names).compact().unique() }}
{{ $input.all().map(x => x.json.to_address).compact().unique() }}
{{ $input.all().map(x => x.json.to_name).compact().unique().filter(item => !item.includes("@") ) }}
</Client Name Strings>

For each individual gift item in the email, please output JSON like the following:
{
  "gifts": [
    {
      "recipient": "Natalie Johnson",
      "item_name": "Sony XM5-1000 Over-Ear Headphones",
      "brand": "Sony",
      "store": "Amazon",
      "price": 349.99,
      "item_type": "Headphones",
      "category": "Electronics",
      "url": "http://amazon.com/itemurl",
      "date_purchased": "2024-04-01",
      "gift_event": "birthday"
    }
  ]
}

"gift_event" values: "birthday" // "mothers_day" // "fathers_day" // "anniversary" // "christmas" // "valentines_day" // "hannukah" // etc // null

If there is only one gift in the email, it should have one item in the array. If there are multiple gifts, the array should have multiple items. If there are no gifts, you may return null for the array.

Return only JSON, nothing else. Do not include triple backticks denoting JSON format, just the raw JSON.

ONLY include "gift_event" if the email text definitively proves the event, e.g. it says "Happy Mother's Day" or "Happy Birthday" in a note field, or the item is a birthday cake or father's day package. Otherwise, leave it null.

<GIFT EMAIL DATA>
Email Thread ID:
{{ $json.thread_id }}

Date:
{{ $json.date }}

Subject:
{{ $json.subject }}

Body:
{{ $json.text }}
</GIFT EMAIL DATA>

